1. Introduction

Our project goal is to investigate the various factors incoming college students may research when deciding when choosing a university they want to attend. However, our study primarily focuses on the top ranked 100 universities in the U.S.

We collected data of the top 104 universities in 2018 from baike.baidu.com which contains data of college names imported from US News. After further manipulation we create 5 variables: college ranking, college name, tuition, enrollment, and whether they were a private or public university. We then combined this dataset with two online sources from Kaggle.com and opendatasoft.com. Combining this information gives us a finalized dataset that contains variables of college ranking, college name, tuition, enrollment, private or public university, and location variables of state and region. We then looked for new databases with other features and found another Kaggle.com source, which contains college variables similar to the ones previously listed, but also includes salary information, population of STEM students, and male-female students ratios. Our finalized dataset contains 104 observations and 12 variables, which we used to conduct analytical investigations on the variables of college name and ranking, enrollment, tuition, school type (public/private) graduation rate, region, salary and diversity.

Furthermore, our goal is to analyze variables that impact university selection choice based on the following three groups: academic quality, costs, and location. We plan to investigate these groups by asking the following questions:

  1. Academic Quality
  1. What is the relationship between university ranking and if the school is private or public?
  2. Do higher ranking schools have a larger student population than lower ranking ones? Is the correlation different between private and public schools?
  3. Do schools with overall higher rankings have a larger population of STEM students?
  4. Are initial salaries and mid-career salaries for recent graduates higher on average if the student graduated from a high ranking school?
  1. Location & Diversity
  1. What region has the highest number of top ranked schools?
  2. Which regions tend to have more diverse student bodies?
  1. Costs
  1. How affordable are high ranking universities?
  2. What is the average cost for the top ranked universities?
  3. What is the average cost of tuition for each region?

Asking these questions segways into our statistical investigation. We hypothesize that private universities on average will have higher rankings and better quality, more expensive tuition, and most likely be concentrated in the Northeast region of the U.S. We also expect to see public universities with relatively cheaper tuition rates compared to private universities, but also a range of good and poor rankings. We chose to investigate U.S. colleges and universities because as college students ourselves, we understand that there are many factors that impact an incoming student’s decision on where to attend for higher education. We hope that our findings can provide insight and may even aid in someone’s college decision in the future.

2. Methodology

2.1 Initializing our table

The table we are using imported data from US NEWS Top 100 Schools webpage, which we obtained from ‘https://baike.baidu.com/item/美国大学综合排名/17602737?fr=aladdin’ to form our initial table. The variables we look at are college ranking, college name, tuition, and enrollment. The key feature of this table is college name (NAME), which we will use to join other datasets.

source1 <- paste0("https://baike.baidu.com/item/美国大学综合排名/17602737?fr=aladdin")
source1_html <- read_html(source1)
source1_tables <- source1_html %>% html_nodes("table")
source1_raw_data <- source1_tables[[3]] %>% html_table() ## find the third table in the website page
names(source1_raw_data) <- c("Ranking","Chinese_Names","NAME","Tuition","Enrollment")
source1_raw_data<-source1_raw_data[-1,]
source1_raw_data<-source1_raw_data[,-2] # delete unnessary rows and columns

2.2 Add Tuition Column

In the tuition column, some schools have both in-state and out-of-state tuition, because it is a public university. We use separate() to split the Tuition column into two separate columns, one being out-of-state tuition and the other in-state tuition (if any). Another variable we created was a Public/Private column which will help with analyzing tuition data. We also further cleaned the tuition column by eliminating $ and , .

# delete in_state tuition
source1_tuition_fix <-source1_raw_data %>% separate('Tuition', c("Tuition", "out_of_state"),sep = "（out-of-state），")
# add a new column: private/public school based on tuition column
for(i in 1:103){
  if(is.na(source1_tuition_fix$out_of_state[i])){
    source1_tuition_fix$out_of_state[i] = "Private"
  } else{
    source1_tuition_fix$out_of_state[i] = "Public"
  }
}
names(source1_tuition_fix) <- c("Ranking","NAME","Tuition","Public/Private","Enrollment")

# data cleaning for tuition column
for(i in 1:103){
  source1_tuition_fix$NAME[i]=toupper(source1_tuition_fix$NAME[i])
  source1_tuition_fix$NAME[i]=source1_tuition_fix$NAME[i] %>% str_replace("--", "-")
  source1_tuition_fix$Tuition[i]=gsub('[,]','',source1_tuition_fix$Tuition[i])
  source1_tuition_fix$Tuition[i]=gsub('[$]','',source1_tuition_fix$Tuition[i])
}

To fix this we manually filled out the missing state information for some colleges.

2.6 Add Female/Male Ratio

Another dataset we want to use contains ratios of Female and Male, however it is not tidy, and we used pivot_wider to reshape the dataset. Then, we use left-join to combine our main_add_salary table with Female/Male Ratio data, by variable NAME. Even though we tried data cleaning by using str_replace and toupper we still have 11 unmatched schools after joining.

Therefore, the male-female ratio is searched on schools’ website for these school: WASHINGTON UNIVERSITY IN ST.LOUIS,EMORY UNIVERSITY,OHIO STATE UNIVERSITY-COLUMBUS,GEORGE WASHINGTON UNIVERSITY,BRIGHAM YOUNG UNIVERSITY-PROVO,UNIVERSITY OF PITTSBURGH,AMERICAN UNIVERSITY,NORTH CAROLINA STATE UNIVERSITY–RALEIGH,INDIANA UNIVERSITY–BLOOMINGTON,STONY BROOK UNIVERSITY–SUNY,SUNY COLLEGE OF ENVIRONMENTAL SCIENCE AND FOREST

‘source5_diversity_table’ database source URL:‘https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/jessemostipak/college-tuition-diversity-and-pay?resource=download’

# Change to your own direction path. database source URL: 
source5_diversity_table <- read.csv(file = '/Users/nguyenthao/Documents/Fall22/SDS322E/Project1/diversity_school.csv')
# Main task:tidying reshaping
source5_diversity_reshape<-source5_diversity_table %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = category, values_from = enrollment)
colnames(source5_diversity_reshape)[1] <- 'NAME'

# data wragling for NAME column
for(i in 1:nrow(source5_diversity_reshape)){
  source5_diversity_reshape$NAME[i]=source5_diversity_reshape$NAME[i] %>% str_replace(" at ", "-")
  source5_diversity_reshape$NAME[i]=toupper(source5_diversity_reshape$NAME[i])
}
main_add_diversity <- main_add_salary %>% left_join(source5_diversity_reshape, by = "NAME")

# change female/male data to porportion format
main_change_ratio<-main_add_diversity%>%
  mutate("Male Ratio"= round(100*(unlist(main_add_diversity$total_enrollment)-unlist(main_add_diversity$Women))/unlist(main_add_diversity$total_enrollment)),2)%>%
  mutate("Female Ratio"= round(100*unlist(main_add_diversity$Women)/unlist(main_add_diversity$total_enrollment)),2)
main_change_ratio<-main_change_ratio[,-c(11:23,25)]

3. Findings and Conclusions

3.1 Academic quality

Analysis 1

Are high ranking schools tend to be private/ public schools?

# Rename the label from Public/ Private to School_Type
main_final_table <- rename(main_final_table, School_Type = 'Public/Private')

# Count the number of private and public schools
main_final_table %>% group_by(School_Type) %>%
  summarise(school_type_count = n())
## # A tibble: 2 × 2
##   School_Type school_type_count
##   <chr>                   <int>
## 1 Private                    59
## 2 Public                     45
# Create a graph of the number of private and public schools
main_final_table %>% group_by(School_Type) %>%
  summarise(school_type_count = n()) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=School_Type, y=school_type_count, fill = School_Type)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity") + ylim(0,65) + 
  labs(title="Count of Private/Public schools", x="School Type", y="Count") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 15, face = "bold", hjust = 0.5))

The plot depicts the number of public and private schools in our data set of top 104 best ranking universities and colleges in the US.There are 59 private schools and 45 public schools in our ranking table, meaning that private schools make a bigger proportion than public schools in this data set.

Analysis 2

Do higher ranking schools (smaller ‘Ranking’ value) have a larger student population than lower ranking ones? Is the correlation different between private and public schools?

#Change data type to numeric
main_final_table$Ranking <- as.numeric(main_final_table$Ranking)
main_final_table$Enrollment <- as.numeric(main_final_table$Enrollment)

#Correlation between ranking and student enrollment
print("Correlation between ranking and student enrollment")
## [1] "Correlation between ranking and student enrollment"
cor(main_final_table$Ranking, main_final_table$Enrollment)
## [1] 0.2596504
#Correlation between ranking and student enrollment, filter by school type
main_final_table %>%
  group_by(School_Type) %>%
  summarise(cor(Ranking, Enrollment))
## # A tibble: 2 × 2
##   School_Type `cor(Ranking, Enrollment)`
##   <chr>                            <dbl>
## 1 Private                          0.150
## 2 Public                          -0.201
#Graphing a table to depict the correlation, considering the School Type
main_final_table %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Enrollment, y = Ranking, color = School_Type)) + 
  geom_point() + geom_smooth(method = "lm") + scale_x_log10() + 
  labs(title="Correlation between Ranking and Enrollment", x="Enrollment", y="Ranking") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 15, face = "bold", hjust = 0.5))

In general, there is very little correlation between school ranking and student enrollment, only 0.26, meaning higher ranking schools (smaller ‘Ranking’ value) have less student enrollment. A graph is created to see if this relationship changes as we consider the schools’ type. From the graph, we can see that for public schools, the lower ranking schools (higher ‘Ranking’ value) have less enrollment then higher ranking schools (cor = -0.2). However, for private schools, higher ranking schools (smaller ‘Ranking’ value) have less enrollment (cor = 0.15). Based on this information, students can decide whether they want to go to a large or small school, and how that would change depends on whether they prefer private or public schools.

Analysis 3

Do schools with overall higher rankings have a larger population of STEM students?

#Compute the correlation to see relationship between school ranking and student proportion in STEM:
print("Correlation between Ranking and percentage of student in STEM")
## [1] "Correlation between Ranking and percentage of student in STEM"
cor(main_final_table$`STEM_Rate(%)`, main_final_table$Ranking, use = "complete.obs")
## [1] -0.210229
# Create a graph:
main_final_table %>% ggplot(aes(x = Ranking, y= `STEM_Rate(%)`, na.rm=TRUE)) + 
  geom_point() + geom_smooth(method = "lm") + ylim(0,105) +
  labs(title="Percentage of student in STEM by school ranking", 
       x="Ranking", y= "STEM rate (%)") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 15, face = "bold", hjust = 0.5))

From the correlation computation, there is little negative correlation between the ranking of a school and the percentage of students in STEM majors, only about -0.21. The same thing can be observed from the graph. This graph and the distribution of the points also indicate that schools have a relatively similar proportion of students in STEM majors, around under 40%. Therefore, students can choose schools in top 100 universities and get into a good STEM environment.

Analysis 4

Do students from higher ranking schools have higher early-career and mid-career salary?

# To see the difference in salary easier, we break the 104 schools into 3 ranking groups and see their salary distribution:
Ranking_breakdown_table <- main_final_table %>%
  mutate(Ranking_breakdown = case_when(Ranking < 37 ~ 'Rank 1-36',
                                       Ranking <69 ~ 'Rank 37-68',
                                       Ranking <105 ~ 'Rank 69-104'))

# Pull out data of min, max, and mean salary of Early-career salary and Mid-career salary:
Ranking_breakdown_table %>% 
  group_by(Ranking_breakdown) %>%
  summarise(
    max_start_salary = max(`Early_Career_Pay($)`, na.rm = TRUE),
    min_start_salary = min(`Early_Career_Pay($)`, na.rm = TRUE),
    mean_start_salary = mean(`Early_Career_Pay($)`, na.rm = TRUE),
    max_mid_salary = max(`Mid_Career_pay($)`, na.rm = TRUE),
    min_mid_salary = min(`Mid_Career_pay($)`, na.rm = TRUE),
    mean_mid_salary = mean(`Mid_Career_pay($)`, na.rm = TRUE)
  ) %>% arrange(Ranking_breakdown)

We divide all 104 schools into 3 groups by their ranking: Rank 1-36 (36 schools), Rank 37-68 (32 schools) and Rank 69-104 (35 schools), with the smaller ‘Ranking’ values meaning more prestigious and higher ranking schools. We then created box plots to compare the distribution of salaries between the 3 groups by early-career salary and mid-career salary. For the early-career salary graph, it is illustrated that students from higher ranking schools earn more than students in lower ranking schools as the 1st group’s mean, max, and 75th percentile salary values are higher than those of the 2nd and 3rd group. More details on the values can be seen from the table created. A similar trend can be observed as we graph the mid-salary data, the only difference is that the salary range has increased. Obtaining a degree from certain colleges is considered prestigious and may make some graduates more qualified than others. Future students should consider school ranking as a decision factor if their goal is to earn more money after graduation.

3.3 Cost

Analysis 1

Affordability of high ranking schools

# Change data type to numeric
main_final_table$`Tuition($)` <- as.numeric(main_final_table$`Tuition($)`)

# Create a graph to see the relationship between tuition and the school ranking
main_final_table %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = `Tuition($)`, y = Ranking, color = School_Type)) + 
  geom_point(size = 2.5) + 
  geom_smooth(method="lm") +
  xlab("Tuition Cost") + 
  ggtitle("Average Tuition of U.S. Universities by Ranking") +
  theme_gray() + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 15, face = "bold", hjust = 0.5)) +
  ylim(0, 100)

This scatter plot visualizes the tuition costs of top ranked U.S. universities plotted against each ranking. Since we interpret the smallest number rankings as being the “highest ranking” schools, from this data we can conclude that the higher a university is ranked, most likely the more expensive it will be. Higher tuition rates coincide with highly ranked programs that have more funding to provide quality education, independent research, and extra-curriculars. By coloring by Public/Private, we can also conclude that schools with the highest ranking are also typically private universities, hence the expensive tuition. The one private school outlier is BYU, where students with certain religious affiliations have reduced tuition rates.
